---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
---

<Base
  title="CV · Xiaochuan Li"
  description="CV of Xiaochuan Li, M.Sc. Human and AI, University of Technology Nuremberg. I test which semantic structures formal linguistics proposes that language models actually build, across three case studies: modals, compounds, and generics."
>
  <header class="mb-10">
    <div class="flex items-baseline justify-between gap-4">
      <h1 class="text-3xl font-medium tracking-tight">Xiaochuan Li</h1>
      <a href="/cv.pdf" class="no-print text-sm text-[var(--color-accent)] hover:underline whitespace-nowrap">Download PDF ↗</a>
    </div>
    <p class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)] mt-1">
      M.Sc. Human and AI · University of Technology Nuremberg
    </p>
    <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-dim)] mt-2">
      <a href="mailto:xiaochuan.li@utn.de" class="hover:text-[var(--color-accent)] transition-colors">xiaochuan.li@utn.de</a>
      · <a href="https://github.com/xchuan-li" class="hover:text-[var(--color-accent)] transition-colors">github.com/xchuan-li</a>
      · Nürnberg, Germany
    </p>
  </header>

  <section class="mb-9">
    <h2 class="text-[11px] uppercase tracking-wider text-[var(--color-text-dim)] font-medium mb-3">Education</h2>
    <div class="space-y-4">
      <div class="flex justify-between gap-4 break-inside-avoid">
        <div>
          <p class="font-medium">M.Sc., Human and AI</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-muted)]">University of Technology Nuremberg (UTN)</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-muted)] mt-1"><span class="font-medium text-[var(--color-text)]">Research focus.</span> Whether language models build the semantic structures formal linguistics proposes (modal force, morphological composition, genericity), or only their surface. I turn each theory's claim into a prediction that controlled intervention and interpretability can decide, testing what competing theories predict rather than crowning one correct.</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-muted)] mt-1"><span class="font-medium text-[var(--color-text)]">Coursework.</span> Cognitive psychology · interpretability · deep learning · epistemology.</p>
        </div>
        <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-dim)] whitespace-nowrap">2025 to 2027</p>
      </div>
      <div class="flex justify-between gap-4 break-inside-avoid">
        <div>
          <p class="font-medium">German language program</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-muted)]">University of Marburg · intensive German for graduate study</p>
        </div>
        <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-dim)] whitespace-nowrap">2024 to 2025</p>
      </div>
      <div class="flex justify-between gap-4 break-inside-avoid">
        <div>
          <p class="font-medium">B.A., Philosophy</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-muted)]">Shenzhen University · College of Humanities</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-muted)] mt-1">
            Senior thesis: <a href="/writing/from-leibniz" class="text-[var(--color-accent)] hover:underline"><em>On Leibniz's Logical Theory</em></a> (advisor: Zang Yong)
          </p>
          <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-muted)] mt-1">
            Coursework: logic, history of philosophy, analytic philosophy, mathematical logic; electives in cognitive psychology and linguistics. Shapes my focus on reasons, causality, and what licenses an inference.
          </p>
        </div>
        <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-dim)] whitespace-nowrap">2020 to 2024</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="mb-9">
    <h2 class="text-[11px] uppercase tracking-wider text-[var(--color-text-dim)] font-medium mb-3">Research: three case studies</h2>
    <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-muted)] mb-4 max-w-prose">One question, three kinds of word where natural language's logic looks unlike the textbook's. Each turns a formal-semantic hypothesis into a causal test read with interpretability.</p>
    <div class="space-y-5">
      <div class="break-inside-avoid">
        <div class="flex justify-between gap-4 items-baseline">
          <p class="font-medium text-[15px]">MODUS: modality</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-dim)] whitespace-nowrap">Master's thesis · pilot run</p>
        </div>
        <p class="text-sm mt-1">Is modal force a set of possible worlds (Kratzer) or a degree of certainty (Lassiter)? A pilot builds a certainty direction from evidence alone, with no modal word; ablating it on a <em>might</em> sentence pushes its certainty toward <em>must</em> (+0.15), while a base-rate control does not. GRADUS, a graded epistemic-force dataset, turns the probe into a calibration diagnostic.</p>
        <p class="text-xs mt-1.5">
          <a href="https://xchuan-li.github.io/research/modus" class="text-[var(--color-accent)] hover:underline">Project page ↗</a>
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="break-inside-avoid">
        <div class="flex justify-between gap-4 items-baseline">
          <p class="font-medium text-[15px]">HanGL: morphological composition</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-dim)] whitespace-nowrap">personal · pilot done</p>
        </div>
        <p class="text-sm mt-1">Is a Sino-Korean word's meaning composed from its Hanja morphemes or memorized whole? Hangul hides the morphemes; Hanja is the answer key the model never sees. A wrong-Hanja intervention shows latent grounding scales with model capability; the forward step tests morphological decomposition against the human psycholinguistics of Sino-Korean.</p>
        <p class="text-xs mt-1.5">
          <a href="https://xchuan-li.github.io/research/hangl" class="text-[var(--color-accent)] hover:underline">Project page ↗</a>
          <span class="text-[var(--color-text-dim)]"> · </span>
          <a href="https://github.com/xchuan-li/HanGL" class="text-[var(--color-accent)] hover:underline">GitHub ↗</a>
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="break-inside-avoid">
        <div class="flex justify-between gap-4 items-baseline">
          <p class="font-medium text-[15px]">ORDO: genericity</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-dim)] whitespace-nowrap">in design</p>
        </div>
        <p class="text-sm mt-1">"Birds fly" is not "all birds fly": a penguin does not falsify it. That default-with-exceptions is an inference classical logic cannot state. Do generics and modals share one ordering-source mechanism for defaults, or two? A layered novelty-of-exception design where either outcome is a real finding.</p>
        <p class="text-xs mt-1.5">
          <a href="https://xchuan-li.github.io/research/ordo" class="text-[var(--color-accent)] hover:underline">Project page ↗</a>
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="mb-9">
    <h2 class="text-[11px] uppercase tracking-wider text-[var(--color-text-dim)] font-medium mb-3">Collaborations</h2>
    <div class="space-y-4 text-sm">
      <div class="break-inside-avoid">
        <p class="font-medium text-[15px]">Latent Control States <span class="font-normal text-[var(--color-text-dim)]">· DFKI</span></p>
        <p class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)] mt-0.5">Does prompt framing shift a causally relevant latent state, or only the output? My contribution: a utilitarian minimal-pair probe — dilemma × benefit-size × framing — testing whether the choice tracks the real stakes or only surface pressure.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="break-inside-avoid">
        <p class="font-medium text-[15px]">Cross-lingual ProtoBias <span class="font-normal text-[var(--color-text-dim)]">· an established NLP group</span></p>
        <p class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)] mt-0.5">Does a vision-language model track meaning, or culture-specific prototype shortcuts? My contribution: the cross-lingual evaluation across seven languages that extends the group's forthcoming paper.
          <a href="https://github.com/xchuan-li/cross_lingual_protobias" class="text-[var(--color-accent)] hover:underline whitespace-nowrap">GitHub ↗</a></p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="mb-9">
    <h2 class="text-[11px] uppercase tracking-wider text-[var(--color-text-dim)] font-medium mb-3">Skills</h2>
    <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-muted)] italic mb-4 max-w-prose">
      Both the engineering my research needs (controlled linguistic data generation, transformer
      model evaluation, intervention-based causal testing, reproducible pipelines) and the
      foundations it draws on: cognitive psychology, linguistics, and logic.
    </p>
    <div class="space-y-3 text-sm">
      <div class="break-inside-avoid">
        <p class="font-medium">Programming &amp; data</p>
        <p class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)]">Python (NumPy, pandas, scikit-learn), Git, LaTeX.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="break-inside-avoid">
        <p class="font-medium">ML / NLP tooling</p>
        <p class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)]">PyTorch and HuggingFace Transformers (working proficiency): model inference, dataset pipelines, LoRA fine-tuning.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="break-inside-avoid">
        <p class="font-medium">Causal &amp; interpretability methods</p>
        <p class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)]">Controlled do-interventions, causal graphs, and shortcut-severing audits; developing behavioral path-tracing.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="break-inside-avoid">
        <p class="font-medium">Cognitive psychology</p>
        <p class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)]">Working foundations in concept learning, cognitive development, and human reasoning, including the developmental literature on modal cognition (Leahy &amp; Carey), which grounds the emergence question the thesis asks.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="break-inside-avoid">
        <p class="font-medium">Linguistics &amp; logic</p>
        <p class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)]">Formal semantics (possible-worlds, modal quantification), modal and predicate logic, and morphology/syntax across isolating, fusional, and agglutinative types; grounded in a philosophy background in logic and philosophy of language.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="break-inside-avoid">
        <p class="font-medium">Linguistic evaluation</p>
        <p class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)]">Designing controlled stimuli for morphology, agreement, dependency structure, and word order across Chinese, German, English, and Japanese.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="mb-9">
    <h2 class="text-[11px] uppercase tracking-wider text-[var(--color-text-dim)] font-medium mb-3">Languages</h2>
    <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-muted)]">Mandarin Chinese (native) · German (C1) · English (C1), spanning isolating, fusional, and analytic types. Learning Japanese, an agglutinative head-final system, to extend the typological span my linguistic work draws on.</p>
  </section>

</Base>
